Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Eustace","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Old French form of the Late Greek names <i>Eustakhios</i> and <i>Eustathios</i>. These were evidently of separate origin, the former derived from <i>eu</i> ‘well, good’ + <i>stakhys</i> ‘grapes’, the latter from <i>eu</i> + <i>stēnai</i> ‘to stand’. However, the tradition is very confused. The name was introduced in this form to Britain by the Normans, among whom it was popular as a result of the fame of  St Eustace , a Norman nobleman who was said to have been converted to Christianity by the vision of a crucifix between the antlers of the stag he was hunting."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Eustace de Mohaut was born in 1027, in Monthault, Ille-et-Vilaine, Brittany, France. He married spouse Eustace de Mohaut before 1050, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1112, in Mold, Flintshire, Wales, at the age of 85."},"et":{"1027–1112":"1027–1112","–Female":"Surnud","1050–1130":"1050–1130","1052–1119":"1052–1119","1058–Male":"1058–Surnud","1060–Male":"1060–Surnud","1070–1141":"1070–1141","about 1070":"umbes 1070","1141":"1141","1130":"1130","1052":"1052","1050":"1050","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","Abt 1052":"umbes 1052","1027":"1027","1058":"1058","1112":"1112","about 1058":"umbes 1058","Abt 1050":"umbes 1050","before 1050":"enne 1050","Abt 1060":"umbes 1060","1119":"1119","